Top picks: BUY: Ferrovial, Vinci, DSV, IAG and AIA. SELL: AENA.
Catalyst Calls: BUY: Wizz Air, SELL: Maersk

Since the publication of our last Transport Leading indicators on \(25^{\text{th}}\) July, the airlines \((+6\%)\) and airport & infra names \((+4\%)\) have continued to outperform the market on average (STOXX \(600 + 1\%\) ). In airlines, Air France- KLM \((+21\%)\) and Wizz Air \((+16\%)\) have been the outperformers, with the latter boosted by changes in strategy announced as part of the 1Q results on \(24^{\text{th}}\) July, thus aiding the performance of our positive catalyst call from \(13^{\text{th}}\) June, meanwhile Ryanair and easyJet (both flat) have been the relative underperformers, seemingly not helped by the lackluster last- minute short- haul fares trends highlighted in our fares tracker. In airports & infra, Fraport (HOLD, \(+12\%\) ) has been the outperformer in spite of an in- line set of 2Q results on \(5^{\text{th}}\) August, with markets cheering a +ve FCF in Q2; meanwhile Vinci (BUY, \(- 6\%\) ) has been the relative underperformer, driven by the recent political turmoil in France. Vinci is now once again trading at c. trough PE relative to CAC, and we note that in history, the stock has outperformed CAC by \(10 - 40\%\) from such levels. In terms of stock selection, we continue to prefer quality names such as IAG and Ryanair in airlines; Vinci, Ferrovial and AIA in airports & infra (all BUY). We also like the recovery potential at Wizz (see our note 'All change please' from \(30^{\text{th}}\) July upgrading to BUY). By contrast, we think the market is ignoring potential medium- term risks to Dora III tariffs with Aena (SELL), plus the potential for airlines, esp. RYA, to trim capacity given the planned tariff increase for 2026. From this month's report we would highlight: (i) intra- EU seats for 3Q25 (slide 56) tracking \(3.7\%\) above 3Q24 unchanged vs. a month ago; (ii) transatlantic ASKs for 3Q25 (slide 58) tracking \(3.5\%\) above 3Q24 vs \(3.4\%\) above a month ago; and (iii) UK spend on air travel (slide 75) having slowed only modestly to \(+5\%\) y- o- y in July vs \(+6\%\) in June, according to Barclaycard.

The freight stocks under our coverage have been weak over the past month, falling by \(6\%\) on average, in spite of some reasonable 2Q reporting, driven by the market's concerns on tariff uncertainty (inc. US de minimis rules - see here on DHL), waning business and consumer confidence, and in turn, a potentially lackluster 2H volume recovery. Indeed, our current dbDatalnsights data, which tracks container volumes in real time, shows MTD August volumes at \(+4.4\%\) vs \(+8.8\%\) in July. Against this backdrop, we continue to highlight DSV (BUY) as our top pick, where the earnings growth is driven by the Schenker deal more so than by current trading (see our note 'Copy, paste' from \(20^{\text{th}}\) August). We also continue to like DHL (BUY) - operationally and financially the business is coping very well against a challenging backdrop, and we are convinced that the company will deliver the targeted €3bn FCF, return it to shareholders and that valuation is attractive. Finally, on the container shipping names, Maersk upgraded its FY'25 guidance as expected whereas Hapag- Lloyd's guidance was more conservative. Spot rates (SCFI) have been falling since mid- June after a short period of volatility due to US- China tariff measures. Since the beginning of June, SCFI has fallen c. \(35\%\) while CCFI (contract and spot rate) have also fallen c. \(16\%\) over last nine weeks. We remain HOLD rated on the container shippers Maersk & Hapag- Lloyd as we expect significant industry overcapacity and uncertain demand to weigh on rates.

Demand growth weak and unpredictable for 2025Last year, containership demand saw some rebound (+6% YoY as per Clarksons or c.19% in TEU miles terms due to re- routing of ships round the horn of Africa). Clarksons forecasts 2025 container ship demand growth of 2.6% as base case scenario (+2.5% in TEU miles). Our latest dbDatalnsights container tracker shows YoY volume growth of c.4% in August (first three weeks) after +8.8% in July, - 0.6% in June and +1.6% in May, which in our view indicates that underlying demand is holding up but is not really strong, driven by a lack of business and consumer confidence.

Idle capacity remained highly volatile in 2020. To match the falling demand during April- June 2020 idle capacity build- up significantly reaching c.6% of the global fleet capacity and if we include capacity out on scrubber retrofits, total capacity out of the market reached 9.3%. **Conclusion**: Significant oversupply is seen in the container shipping industry in recent years owing to large orders placed since 2021. The top 10 players, which have c.84% market share, have c.21% of current global fleet capacity on order. To this,if we add orders placed through charter owners and confirmed to be operated by one of the Top 10 players, we estimate around 25% of the current global fleet (approx. 80% of the orderbook) is on order by the Top 10 players. Orderbook as a percentage of current fleet stands high at 30.7% due to large orders placed since mid-2024.

Clarksons data suggests a 7% increase in gross capacity (on the year-end 2024 fleet) is projected for 2025, followed by a 5% rise in 2026. Scrapping activity is minimal, estimated at a mere 10k TEUs of the current global fleet in 2025. Idle capacity is also low, currently sitting at c.2% of the global fleet.

With the help of proprietary work from our dbDatalnsights research team and the use of automatic identification systems (AIS) data, we are able to track "near real time" movements of all container ships globally. We track container ships in and out of 84 ports globally and then, using our dbDatalnsights propriety algorithms, we model the number of containers handled (what comes on and off) at a port. As such, we are able to get an almost real time indicator of container demand and therefore economic activity. Our data matches data from the Institute of Shipping Economics and Logistics (ISL) which samples throughput at some 60 ports across the world but is only published on a monthly basis with a lag of several weeks.
Our latest dbDatalnsights container tracker shows YoY volume growth of c.4% in August (first three weeks) after \(+8.8\%\) in July, \(- 0.6\%\) in June and \(+1.6\%\) in May.

3. Container throughput volumes at US ports remained strong with Long Beach \((+7.0\%)\) and Los Angeles \((+8.5\%)\) both reporting volume growth YoY.
4. Santos July volumes were strong at \(+8.5\%\) YoY bringing YTD volume growth to c. \(8\%\) .

Conclusion: Global container throughput volumes are holding up, going by our ports sample and dbDatalnsights data and ISL index however demand is not really strong, driven by a lack of business and consumer confidence. Clarksons forecasts 2025 container ship demand growth of 2.6% (base case) on capacity growth of 6.6%. Demand in TEU miles is estimated to grow broadly in line at 2.5% (after increasing c.19% in 2024). The full year scenario is difficult to predict given the uncertainty around tariffs agreements and unwinding of the Red Sea situation. Volumes on Transpacific route declined significantly YoY in April however with the tariff pause, less contraction is expected for rest of the year, assuming tariffs remain manageable. At present, rerouting of ships is estimated to be adding c.11% to overall demand (in TEU miles). For 2026, early indications are for supply growth of 4.4% on demand growth +2.7%.

We take a top-down approach to forecast demand starting with our world GDP forecasts from our DB economists and apply a multiplier of 1.0x to 1.5x to real GDP. Our house view on World GDP growth is at +3.0% and +3.1% for 2025 and 2026.

With the help of proprietary work from our dbDatalnsights research team we are able to track container ship port calls and average duration spent by ships at 8 major global ports. Both of these are indicators of port congestion. There is a strong inverse correlation between the average time spent by a container ship at port and the number of port calls made i.e. port congestion would mean more time spent by a ship at a port, which eventually leads to lower port calls. We also find that port congestion is one of the factors that have helped freight rates to increase to record highs in past few months.

From our analysis, port congestion (measured as median time that a ship has spent at a port) started in October 2020 and by 2023, situation normalized and reached pre- covid levels of around 28 hours in 2023. There is some congestion in European and South American ports which has led to an increase in Aug (MTD) port duration time to around 33.8 hours.

The China Containerised Freight Index (CCFI) collects export data from 10 major Chinese ports and includes both contract and spot rates and widely seen as a good balanced barometer of the trade lanes out of China.

Created by the Chinese government in 2005, the Shanghai Containerised Freight Index (SCFI) is based on the spot rates of the Shanghai export container market based on the data compiled from 15 different shipping routes. Once the index was established it allowed market participants to trade derivatives against its movements. The base date of the data is 16 October 2009 and set to 1,000 points. The data is generally released by the Shanghai Shipping Exchange every Friday at 15:00 Beijing time.
The main difference of between the SCFI and CCFI are:

- Geographical coverage: SCFI is a weighted average of 15 different shipping routes from Shanghai, typically to Northern Europe, compared to the CCFI which reflects China's export container movements as the sample is taken across 10 Chinese ports, not just Shanghai.

- Different target market: SCFI is based on the spot rates of Shanghai's export container market on just 15 routes (mainly to North Europe) and therefore is a much narrower sample that tends to be more volatile compared to the CCFI which targets the overall freight rates (including spot and contractual rates) of China's export container transport market (10 ports sampled)
Both the CCFI and CCFI indices can be found at the following Shanghai Shipping Index - http://en.sse.net.cn/indices/ccfinew.jsp.

We note that the business mix of the European listed container shipping companies, Maersk Line (AP Moller Maersk Group) and Hapag- Lloyd, have strong exposure to other trade lines, particularly in the Atlantic (North and South America) and Africa trades. In 2022 Maersk's \(31.6\%\) of total transported volumes came from the North- South trade lane ( \(46\%\) East- West and \(22.5\%\) Intra- regional). Therefore, the conclusions arising from the readings of the CCFI and the SCFI cannot be entirely extrapolated to the specific actual freight rates of those companies. An example of this was is 2016, when the CCFI and SCFI continued to rise towards the back end of the year, but Maersk reported much softer freight rates as the freight rate environment on the North- South trade lanes was much weaker.

In order to complement the weekly readings of the CCFI and the SCFI, we obtain the monthly readings of the Container Trades Statistics (CTS) who is the exclusive agent of World Liner Data Limited (WLDL) for other trade lines from Bloomberg. However, we have access to those readings with approximately 1.5 months' delay and whilst they give us a good reading on trade lanes, the data is more lagged compared to both the CCFI and SCFI.

Bunker cost typically account for around \(14\%\) of container shipper's cost base but it can be volatile. In 2024, bunker costs were higher than normal due to rerouting of ships and longer routes. We track Marine Fuel Oil (MFO) Rotterdam 380 spot bunker prices in US\\$/MT and also \(0.1\%\) European gasoline CIF NEW cargo in US\\$/MT. There is an environmental shift towards greener fuels, such as low sulphur and LNG solutions with IMO2020, a carriage ban on fuel \(>0.5\%\) (currently cap at \(3.5\%\) ) from March 2020 and Carbon Intensity Indicator (CII) from January 2023. The price of marine or bunker fuel fluctuates largely in line with crude oil prices, which are subject to a number of economic and political factors. Container shipping companies can also protect themselves from the fluctuations in fuel price by hedging. For example, Hapag- Lloyd hedges up to a maximum of \(80\%\) of its bunker costs. The container shipping companies are still working out how to deal with the low sulphur regulations with some companies adding scrubbers to vessels, which is effective but others holding back due to the high costs of installation and now reduced economic benefit of scrubbers following the fall in oil prices. Overall, we would expect most container ships to be running on low sulphur bunker fuel.

- Maersk 
- the vast majority of vessels will comply with the low sulphur cap using low sulphur fuels. Maersk secured a substantial long-term biomethanol fuel agreement in 2024, with the initial deliveries anticipated in 2026. These agreements now cover over half of Maersk's projected dual-fuel methanol fleet needs for 2027.

- Hapag-Lloyd 
- company expects more than \(90\%\) of the world's container fleet will run on compliant fuels. Hapag-Lloyd is currently operating at \(77\%\) on low sulphur fuel (incl. MDO) as at 9M 2024 (64% at MFO \(0.5\%\) , 5% at MFO \(0.1\%\) and 8% at MDO) and high sulphur fuel accounts for \(23\%\) of the current bunker consumption.

StockValuationA.P. Moller MaerskIn our view, a sum-of-the-parts model is the most appropriate and widely-used valuation approach for a company like Maersk. In setting our target price, we establish an assessed valuation for each division based on multiples (mostly EV/IC and EV/EBITDA multiples) compared with similar peers in the sector. For the Ocean division, we use 0.4x EV/IC (below the historical average multiple for container shipping sector of 0.6x to reflect the oversupply and cash burn in the industry) and, for the Logistics & Services division, we use 6.0x EV/EBITDA (slightly below peer group valuations for logistics companies to reflect underperform ing revenue growth and margin stability). We use year-end 2027E net cash as we expect the company to burn cash.Hapag-LloydIn our view, given the volatility in the Hapag-Lloyd's cashflows, we think that a multiple based approach is the best way of valuing the company. We use a multiple based valuation approach to value Hapag-Lloyd taking the average of the followin valuation metrics: 1) EV/Capital employed; 2) P/Book value and EV/EBITDA (using a historical average multiple of 6x).DSVWe use an EV/EBITA based valuation of 9x for 2026 which is aroud 20% below the company's pre-COVID high of c24x. This reflects the strong growth outlook that we think DSV can realise post its acquisition of Schenker which is expected to be fully integrated by 2028. We expect an EBITA CAGR growth of >20% from 2024 to 2028 and expect that the multiple will fall quickly on the back of this strong growth.Kuehne-NagelWe value KNN shares by applying an average historical c. 16x EV/EBIT multiple (3 to 19x between 2010 and 2019) to derive our target price.DHL GroupGiven the five different business units in DHL, our target price is based on a 2026 SOTP valuation and we use peer group multiples to value the five divisions 1) P&P Germany (Post and Parcel), 2) DHL Express, 3) DHL Global Forwarding, 4) DHL Supply and 5) DHL eCommerce Solutions. We value these divisions using multiples of the nearest peers. We then deduct net debt, pension provisions and minorities to arrive at our equity valuation.IAGWe set our TP for IAG by applying a 2026E EV/EBITDA multiple of 4.0x, so at the low end of the 0-year historical average range for the 1-year forward multiple pre-pandemic, and discounting back at 15% per annum. While a higher multiple could be justified and achieved over the medium term, we think this is a realistic target multiple on a 2-month view.LufthansaWe set our TP for Lufthansa by applying a 2026E EV/EBITDA multiple of 3.5x and discounting back at 15%per annum. 3.5x is a 2.5% discount to the 0-year historical average 1-year forward multiple pre-COVID - we think this discount is appropriate given the demanding P/E multiples implied if no discount is applied, based on our latest earnings forecasts.Air France-KLMWe set our TP for AF-KLM by applying a 2026E EV/EBITDA multiple of 3.0x and discounting back at 15% per annum. 3.0x represents a ~30% discount to the 0-year historical average 1-year forward multiple pre-COVID. We think this discount is appropriate given the very demanding P/E multiples implied if no discount were applied, based on our latest earnings forecasts.easyJetWe set our TP for easyJet by applying a FY26E EV/EBITDA multiple of 3.3x, so a 50% discount to the long-term historical average 1-year forward multiple of ~6.5x (ex GFC & COVID), and discounting back at 10%per annum. We think such a discount is appropriate given the demanding P/E multiples implied if no discount is applied, based on our latest earnings forecasts.RyanairWe set our TP for Ryanair by applying a FY27E EV/EBITDA multiple of 7.5x, so in-line with the long-term historical average 1-year forward multiple, and discounting back at 10%per annum.Wizz AirWe set our TP for Wizz by applying a FY27E EV/EBITDA multiple of 4.7x and discounting back at 10% per annum. This multiple represents a ~35% discount to the 7.5x long-term historical average multiple of Ryanair which has the longer trading history. We think the discount we apply to Wizz is appropriate given the higher relative risks we currently perceive, linked to high financial leverage, cost control and the GTF engine issues.FraportWe value Fraport's equity using our DCF model. We assume a risk-free rate of 2.5%, a risk premium of 9.0%, a beta of 10x, leading to our cost of equity at 11.5%. We assume a cost of debt at 3.5% (blended), tax rate at 24% and a target equity ratio of 55% to drive our WACC of 7.5%. We use medium-term growth of 14% and a terminal growth rate of 2%, which should prove reasonable, with an equal mix from traffic and pricing, to perpetuity.Groupe ADPWe value Groupe ADP on a DCF. Our WACC of 7.3% is based on a risk-free rate of 2.9%, risk premium of 7.1%, beta of 0.95x and a cost of debt at 2.5%. We factor in a target equity ratio of 70%, a medium-term growth rate of 3%, and a terminal growth rate of 2% (no minimal GDP growth to perpetuity).AenaWe value Aena's business with a DCF. We use a 2.5% risk-free rate, with a risk premium of 9.7%. With our beta of 0.9, our cost of equity lands at 11.2%. We assume a cost of debt at 2.5%, tax rate at 23% and a target equity ratio of 70% to drive our WACC of 8.4%. We use a terminal growth rate of 2%, which should prove reasonable, with an equal mix from traffic and pricing to perpetuity.Flughafen Zurich AGWe value Flughafen Zurich's equity with a DCF model, and use the implied multiples valuation as a sense-check. We use a risk-free rate of 0.4% (Swiss 10yr yields), a risk premium of 9.6%, a beta of 0.83x, leading to our cost of equity at 8.3%. We assume a cost of debt at 2% (blended), tax rate at 20.4% and a target equity ratio of 75% to drive our WACC of 6.7%. We use medium-term growth of 3%, and a terminal growth rate of 2%.Vinci SAWe value Vinci using a sum-of-the-parts analysis, using the following main methodologies for the different elements: Vinci Autoroutes - DCF model for A/S/EsCo ta and Cofiroute using a 6.3%WACC, and 'Arcou and other' at 6x 2026e EV/EBITDA; Gatwick Airport - DCF valuation using a 6.8%WACC and 12% terminal growth rate; ANA (Portugal) Airports - DCF with a 6.3%WACC out to 2063 with no terminal value; ADP stake - value 8% equity stake at DBe price target; OMA, Edinburgh at 9-10x 2026e EBITDA Other concessions - 10x 2026e EV/EBITDA; Vinci Construction at 7.5x 2026e EV/EBITDA; Vinci Energies we value using a DCF with 10.7% WACC and a 12% terminal growth rate; Vinci Immobilier we value at 9.0x 2026e EV/EBITDA; and Equity Accounted investments we value at both value.AIAWe value AIA equity using an SOTP, with the Air segment normalised Net income (5% RoE) discounted by the cost of equity. We use a risk-free rate of 3%, a risk premium of 9% and a beta of 0.6x to drive our 8.4%cost of equity. We also factor in the balance of under-earnings as on date. For the Non-air segment, we apply 17.5x P E (10% discount to peer mid-cycle to reflect muted growth near term) to get to our equity valuation for the group.FerrovialWe base our TP on a SoTP model. We use a DCF to equity or a DDM model until the end of the concession period for the main toll road assets, an EV/EBITDA for other Concessions/ Construction and Energy, and BV or discount to market value for other investments.

Macroeconomic fluctuations often account for most of the risks associated with exposures to instruments that promise to pay fixed or variable interest rates. For an investor who is long fixed- rate instruments (thus receiving these cash flows), increases in interest rates naturally lift the discount factors applied to the expected cash flows and thus cause a loss. The longer the maturity of a certain cash flow and the higher the move in the discount factor, the higher will be the loss. Upside surprises in inflation, fiscal funding needs, and FX depreciation rates are among the most common adverse macroeconomic shocks to receivers. But counterparty exposure, issuer creditworthiness, client segmentation, regulation (including changes in assets holding limits for different types of investors), changes in tax policies, currency convertibility (which may constrain currency conversion, repatriation of profits and/or liquidation of positions), and settlement issues related to local clearing houses are also important risk factors. The sensitivity of fixed- income instruments to macroeconomic shocks may be mitigated by indexing the contracted cash flows to inflation, to FX depreciation, or to specified interest rates - these are common in emerging markets. The index fixings may - by construction - lag or mis- measure the actual move in the underlying variables they are intended to track. The choice of the proper fixing (or metric) is particularly important in swaps markets, where floating coupon rates (i.e., coupons indexed to a typically short- dated interest rate reference index) are exchanged for fixed coupons. Funding in a currency that differs from the currency in which coupons are denominated carries FX risk.
